Tier 1 — Foundational gaps (the "I can use this without help" bar)
1. Responsive editing (desktop / tablet / mobile)
The single biggest feature you don't have. Every Elementor/Webflow user expects it. Implementation: extend ElementStyle to { base: ElementStyle, sm?: Partial<ElementStyle>, md?: Partial<ElementStyle> }, add device toggle to the topbar, scope iframe width to device, and tag each style control with the active breakpoint. Without this, mobile sites look broken — and most of your traffic is mobile.

2. Inline text editing in the canvas
Double-click a heading → edit in place (contentEditable), tab/escape to commit. Currently every text change is a round-trip through the right panel — slow and breaks flow. Their site is mostly text; this matters more than colors.

3. Section quick actions: drag-reorder, duplicate, delete
You already have dnd-kit installed. Add drag handles in the sidebar, plus a hover toolbar (⋮ menu) on each section in the canvas with Duplicate / Delete / Move-up / Move-down. "Duplicate" alone saves 80% of new-section building because clients copy what works.

4. Undo/redo with Ctrl+Z
Critical for confidence. Your Zustand store can wrap each mutation in a history stack — keep the last ~50 page snapshots. Anyone editing live and afraid of breaking things won't experiment without this.

5. Right-click element menu
Copy style → Paste style → Duplicate → Hide → Delete. Power feature that feels like a desktop app and pays for itself the first time someone wants two buttons to match.

Tier 2 — Templates & presets (so they don't start from blank)
6. Pre-built section variants ("starter blocks")
Instead of "Add Hero" → blank component, offer 6-8 hero variants: "Hero with image right", "Centered with video bg", "Split with stats", "Donation hero". Same for CTA, features, etc. Stored as JSON snippets in your section registry. Welfare/Jamiya clients aren't designers — they want to pick, then tweak.

7. Saved styles / shared presets
"Save this button style" → reusable across the site. When a client tweaks one CTA to perfection, they want all 12 CTAs to match without redoing it. Implementation: a styles table per website, ElementStyle snapshots with a name.

8. Color palette presets
Curated 4-5 color sets for Islamic/welfare brands (Emerald + Gold, Indigo + Ochre, etc.). One click sets color.primary, color.accent, color.background tokens. The token system is already there — you just need the picker UI on the Theme page.

9. Spacing presets per section
Buttons in the section style panel: "Compact / Comfortable / Spacious / Custom". Sets padding_top/bottom for the whole section. Clients don't think in rem.

Tier 3 — UX polish that signals "pro tool"
10. Element tree / breadcrumb in the right panel
At the top of the element style panel, show Section › Container › Heading. Click any segment to jump up. Helps when nested elements get confusing — which they do as sections grow.

11. Hover/Focus state tabs for buttons
Above the button's Typography group: tabs Normal | Hover. Stores hover as a sibling field on ElementStyle. CSS via :hover pseudo at render time. Without this, every button looks dead.

12. Empty-state placeholders in the canvas
When a hero has no image, show a "Click to add background image" dashed box instead of nothing. Same for empty headings. Currently the canvas hides empty fields, which makes them invisible to non-developers.

13. Tooltips on every control
A ? icon next to "Letter spacing" → hover shows "Space between characters. Use small negative values for tighter headings." Half your audience doesn't know what padding-x means. Tooltips are 30 minutes of work and dramatically reduce support requests.

14. Keyboard shortcuts overlay
Cmd+S save, Cmd+P preview, Cmd+D duplicate, Cmd+/ show shortcut sheet. Pro feel without much code.

Tier 4 — Quality & trust features
15. Accessibility contrast checker
When the user picks text colour, show a small badge: "AA ✓ / AA ✗" comparing it to the section background. Most clients don't think about this and produce unreadable sites. ~50 lines of code.

16. SEO + social preview panel
Already have seo_json in the page schema — surface it in the page editor with a live "Google search result" preview and "Facebook share card" preview. Clients don't open dev tools to check OG tags.

17. Page-level + global areas (header / footer)
Right now everything is per-page. A header/footer is the same on 20 pages — clients edit it 20 times. Add a "Global" toggle on a section that makes it appear on every page (or a sub-tree of pages).

18. Repeater fields
Your feature-grid has fixed feature_1, feature_2, feature_3 slots. Schema-level repeater (features: { type: "repeater", min: 1, max: 12 }) so clients can add a 4th feature. Mentioned in your own code comment as "once the engine supports repeater fields, we'll switch."

19. Image cropper in the media library
Right now uploads are whatever shape they uploaded. A crop UI before saving (or as an edit action) keeps hero ratios consistent without Photoshop.

Tier 5 — Differentiation (Islamic/welfare-specific)
20. Hijri date picker + Arabic numeral toggle
For event sections, fatwa dates, etc.

21. Donation widget section
First-class section with goal + progress + Stripe/PayPal/Razorpay handlers. The donations toggle is already on the user model — wire a section to it.

22. Quranic verse / Hadith block
Section with an Arabic + translation field, automatically right-aligned, with a curated Arabic font. Niche, but exactly what your target market wants and nobody else builds for them.

My recommendation for what to build next
If I were you, in this order — each delivers value before you start the next:

Undo/redo + section duplicate/delete/reorder (1-2 days, unblocks everything else)
Responsive editing (1 week, most-requested missing feature)
Inline text editing in canvas (2-3 days, biggest "wow" moment for non-technical users)
Starter blocks per section (2-3 days of designing + JSON authoring, hugest velocity boost for clients)
Tooltips + element breadcrumb (1 day, makes the existing panel feel finished)
After that you have a tool that competes with the cheap end of Elementor/Wix for the Islamic-welfare niche.

Want me to start on any of these? I'd suggest undo/redo + section actions first since they're cheap, broadly useful, and the foundation other features build on.